{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563389"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:57:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:57:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16753"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16753"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0,0.07,0.02,0.89]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110295"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9444"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92566"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5681"},{"type":"tags","id":"8151"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43659"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110295"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with metastatic breast cancer. She dies during the admission. The next day, her sister telephones the ward requesting details about the patient\u0027s final hours and cause of death. The sister explains that she was estranged from the patient for many years but wants closure. There is no documented next of kin or advance care directive. The medical record shows the patient had explicitly stated she did not want her family to know about her diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate response to the sister\u0027s request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reveal only that the death was due to natural causes","Share details as it may help with the sister\u0027s grieving process","Disclose only the time of death","Provide full details as the duty of confidentiality ends at death","Inform her that no information can be provided without documented authority"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario addresses the ethical and legal obligations regarding patient confidentiality after death in Australia. The key principle is that healthcare providers must maintain confidentiality even after a patient dies, particularly when there are explicit wishes from the patient regarding information sharing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInform her that no information can be provided without documented authority\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct approach. This aligns with Australian privacy legislation and professional obligations. The appropriate authority would typically be the executor of the estate or someone with legal authority (such as an enduring power of attorney) to access the deceased\u0027s information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide full details as the duty of confidentiality ends at death\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Under Australian law, the duty of confidentiality continues after death, typically for 30 years, and healthcare providers must respect the wishes of the deceased regarding their medical information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisclose only the time of death\u003C/strong\u003E would still constitute a breach of confidentiality given the patient\u0027s explicit wishes. Even basic information about a patient requires proper authority for disclosure under Australian privacy principles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShare details as it may help with the sister\u0027s grieving process\u003C/strong\u003E, while well-intentioned, would violate both professional ethics and Australian privacy law. The patient\u0027s right to confidentiality takes precedence over the family\u0027s desire for information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReveal only that the death was due to natural causes\u003C/strong\u003E would still breach confidentiality and go against the patient\u0027s expressed wishes. Any disclosure of medical information, even in general terms, requires proper authority under Australian legislation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Australia, the management of health information for deceased individuals varies across states and territories, but generally, confidentiality obligations remain in place for a specified duration, often 30 years after death. Here\u0027s a summary by jurisdiction:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVictoria\u003C/strong\u003E: Protects health information for up to 30 years post-death, with disclosure only to authorised legal representatives aligning with the deceased\u0027s known wishes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENew South Wales\u003C/strong\u003E: Extends privacy protections for 30 years, with disclosure limited to legal representatives or specific legal circumstances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQueensland\u003C/strong\u003E: Ensures confidentiality of deceased individuals\u0027 health data; disclosure typically requires legal authorisation, but no explicit time limit is stated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWestern Australia\u003C/strong\u003E: Upholds confidentiality for deceased patients, restricting disclosure to authorised persons or court orders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESouth Australia\u003C/strong\u003E: Maintains confidentiality for deceased patients, adhering to ethical obligations and legal authorisation requirements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETasmania\u003C/strong\u003E: No direct provisions for deceased individuals, but confidentiality practices align with other states through healthcare policies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAustralian Capital Territory (ACT)\u003C/strong\u003E: Ensures privacy for deceased individuals but provides no specific postmortem timeframe; decisions are guided by policies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENorthern Territory\u003C/strong\u003E: Protects confidentiality for deceased individuals, requiring legal authorisation for access.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA reference to each specific Act can be found in the references below.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Healthcare providers must maintain patient confidentiality even after a patient\u0027s death.","Disclosure of medical information requires explicit patient consent or legal authority.","Breaching confidentiality may only occur when there is a clear public interest or legal requirement to do so."],"references":["Health Records Act 2001 (Vic). Victorian Legislation. Available at: https://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/in-force/acts/health-records-act-2001","Health Records and Information Privacy Act 2002 (NSW). NSW Legislation. Available at: https://legislation.nsw.gov.au/view/html/inforce/current/act-2002-071","Information Privacy Act 2009 (Qld). Queensland Legislation. Available at: https://www.legislation.qld.gov.au/view/html/inforce/current/act-2009-014","Health Services Act 2016 (WA). Western Australian Legislation. Available at: https://www.legislation.wa.gov.au/legislation/statutes.nsf/main_mrtitle_13844_homepage.html","Health Care Act 2008 (SA). South Australian Legislation. Available at: https://www.legislation.sa.gov.au/","Personal Information Protection Act 2004 (Tas). Tasmanian Legislation. Available at: https://www.legislation.tas.gov.au/view/html/inforce/current/act-2004-046","Health Records (Privacy and Access) Act 1997 (ACT). ACT Legislation Register. Available at: https://www.legislation.act.gov.au/a/1997-125/","Information Act 2002 (NT). Northern Territory Legislation. Available at: https://legislation.nt.gov.au/Legislation/INFORMATION-ACT-2002"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92566"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16753"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92566"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T15:13:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T15:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9444"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110295"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":nul